<BLOCK1><TI>RESPONDING PARTY'S FACTUM</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The Respondent, Lois Virgo, (&ldquo;Ms Virgo&rdquo;) opposes the Applicant's Motion for Summary Judgment against her for the sum of $12,087.05, together with pre-judgment and post-judgment interest from April 9, 2009, the date on which the Plaintiff obtained Default Judgment against, <EM>inter alia</EM>, Ms Virgo, as a personal guarantor of the Plaintiff's business loan to Renatoneil Consultants Ltd., (&ldquo;Renatoneil&rdquo;) a company owned and operated by Ms Virgo's former spouse, Jeremy Virgo (&ldquo;Mr. Virgo&rdquo;) the sole owner, operator and directing mind of the said company.</P>
<P>2. Pursuant to the <EM>Canadian Small Business Financing Act</EM>, S.C. 1998, c.36, the Plaintiff, entered into a Credit Agreement for Business (the &ldquo;Loan&rdquo;) with Renatoneil on November 29, 2004.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Motion Record, Tab B, at paragraphs 5a, 6 and 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>3. The Plaintiff obtained Default Judgment against the Defendants in September, 2009.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Affidavit of Lois Virgo, sworn August 9, 2017, Responding Record, Tab A, paragraph 15</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>4. In May 2014, Ms Virgo learned of the existence of the Plaintiff's Claim, Default Judgment and its Writ of Execution (the &ldquo;Writ&rdquo;) against her when she attempted to purchase a home for herself and her son.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Affidavit of Lois Virgo, sworn August 9, 2017, Responding Record, Tab A, paragraph 15</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>5. Negotiations between counsel herein regarding the withdrawal of the Writ in order for Ms Virgo's then pending purchase to close in early July 2014 and the setting aside of Default Judgment against her remained at an impasse until late June 2014, when counsel for Ms Virgo was forced to serve motion materials for the setting aside of the Plaintiff's Default Judgment and withdrawal of its Writ.</P>
<P>6. Only upon being served, did the Plaintiff consent to withdraw and re-register its Writ thereby enabling Ms Virgo's purchase to be completed.</P>
<P>7. The Plaintiff persistently litigated this matter, including the issue of service notwithstanding the fact that it learned that Ms Virgo moved from the matrimonial home approximately nine month before the Plaintiff's action was commenced, and the Plaintiff knew that Ms. Virgo was served with notice of the subject claim at the corporate offices of Renatoneil even though it knew that Ms Virgo was not an officer, director or in any way involved with the business activities of the co-defendants.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Affidavit of Lois Virgo, sworn August 9, 2017, Responding Record, Tab A, paragraphs 4 and 5</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>8. The Plaintiff also continues to litigate enforcement of the Guarantee notwithstanding it is aware of the circumstances underlying the Guarantee and the hardship this litigation is inflicting upon Ms Virgo and her son.</P>
<P>9. Only the issue of Ms Virgo's liability, if any, pursuant the Guarantee remains to be determined; and while in the first instance the signed Guarantee may appear determinative, genuine issues pertaining to the adequacy, sufficiency and independence of the legal advice provided to Ms Virgo in respect of the Guarantee exists and require a trial.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Affidavit of Lois Virgo, sworn August 9, 2017, Responding Record, Tab A, paragraphs 6&ndash;11</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;SUMMARY OF FACTS</TI>
<P>10. Ms Virgo has never been an officer, director, shareholder or a participant (active or otherwise) in the Company, any of Mr. Virgo's business enterprises, or Mr. Virgo's financial Affairs, before or during their marriage.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Affidavit of Lois Virgo, sworn August 9, 2017, Responding Record, Tab A, paragraphs 4 and 5</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>11. On November 29, 2004, Mr. Virgo and the Plaintiff entered into a Credit Agreement for Business, pursuant to the <EM>Canadian Small Business Financing Act</EM>, <UNDER>S.C</UNDER>. 1998, c.36.</P>
<P>12. In late January 2005, Mr. Virgo contacted Ms Virgo while she was overseas visiting her parents and advised her that the Plaintiff required her signature as his spouse on a business loan document and it was imperative that she tend to this matter as soon as she received the document which he would send to her.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Affidavit of Lois Virgo, sworn August 9, 2017, Responding Record, Tab A, paragraph 6</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>13. To this end, Mr. Virgo couriered the Plaintiff's Guarantee of a Term Loan for Business form (the &ldquo;Guarantee&rdquo;) to Ms Virgo, arranged for her meet with a lawyer in Jamaica that week and instructed Ms Virgo to courier the signed document back to him immediately after it had been executed.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Affidavit of Lois Virgo, sworn August 9, 2017, Responding Record, Tab A, paragraphs 7&ndash;11</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. Ms Virgo reviewed the document on her own when it was received, and on February 2, 2005 she met with a lawyer in Jamaica, Yolande J. Whitely, (&ldquo;Whitely&rdquo;) who briefly reviewed it with her and witnessed Ms Virgo's execution of the Guarantee.</P>
<P>15. Neither the actual loan agreement, a summary of its terms, the security documentation nor the loan commitment were provided to Ms Virgo.</P>
<P>16. Whitely made no mention of the profound legal impact of the Guarantee, nor the significance of its consequences, and she did not indicate that it would be in Ms Virgo's best interest to seek modification of the Guarantee.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Affidavit of Lois Virgo, sworn August 9, 2017, Responding Record, Tab A, paragraph 11</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. Whitely was not then, is not now, nor has she ever been a member of member of the Ontario Bar or a Licencee as defined by the <EM>Law Society Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c L.8
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Affidavit of Lois Virgo, sworn August 9, 2017, Responding Record, Tab A, paragraph 10</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>18. Section 12 of the Guarantee provides that:
<QUOTE><P>All debts and liabilities, present and future, of the Customer to the Guarantor are hereby assigned to the Bank and postponed to the guaranteed liabilities, and all moneys received by the Guarantor in respect thereof shall be received in trust for the Bank and forthwith upon receipt shall be paid over to the Bank, the whole without in any way lessening or limiting the liability of the Guarantor under this guarantee; and this assignment and postponement is independent of the guarantee and shall remain in full force and effect until repayment in full to the Bank of all the guaranteed liabilities, notwithstanding that the liability of the undersigned or any of them under this guarantee may have been discharged or terminated.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Motion Record, Tab 2, section 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. Section 13 of the Guarantee provides that:
<QUOTE><P>The undersigned or any of them, if more than one, or his or their executors or administrators, by giving thirty days' notice in writing to the branch of the Bank at which the main account of the Customer is kept, may terminate his or their further liability under this guarantee in respect of liabilities of the Customer incurred or arising after the expiration of such thirty days, but not in respect of any guaranteed liabilities incurred or arising before the expiration of such thirty days even though not then matured; provided that notwithstanding receipt of any such notice the Bank may fulfil any requirements of the Customers based on agreements express or implied made prior to the expiration of such thirty days and any resulting liabilities shall be covered by this guarantee; and provide further that in the event of the termination of this guarantee as to one or more of the undersigned, if more than one, it shall remain a continuing guarantee as to the other or others of the undersigned.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Motion Record, Tab 2, section 13.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>20. Section 15 of the Guarantee provides that:
<QUOTE><P>This guarantee shall be governed in all respects by the law of the province in which the Customer's main account with the Bank is kept.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Motion Record, Tab 2, section 15.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>21. The meaning, legal significance, operation nor consequences of the sections 12 and 13 in particular, as well as other sections in the Guarantee, were not specifically addressed in Whitely's approximately 15 minute meeting with Ms Virgo. Consequently, the Guarantee itself, was not recalled by Ms Virgo when she initiated divorce proceedings against Mr. Virgo.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Affidavit of Lois Virgo, sworn August 9uly, 2017, Responding Record, Tab A, paragraphs 11 and 16</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>22. In September 2008, upon learning that Mr. Virgo had a two year old child with his business partner, Ms Virgo and her son moved from the matrimonial home and in December 2011 she petitioned for divorce.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Affidavit of Lois Virgo, sworn August 9, 2017, Responding Record, Tab A, paragraphs 14 and 15</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>23. Neither Ms Virgo's Net Family Property Statement or her Divorce Order make any mention of, nor do they take into account, any indebtedness incurred by Ms Virgo on behalf of Mr. Virgo, the Company and, in particular, pursuant to the Guarantee.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Affidavit of Lois Virgo, sworn August 9, 2017, Responding Record, Tab A, paragraphs Tab 1</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;THE LAW</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Summary Judgment</TI>
<P>24. The court shall grant a motion for summary judgment if, the court is satisfied that there is no genuine issue requiring a trial with respect to a claim or defence.
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Rules of Civil Procedure, R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 194, as amended R. 20.04(2)(a)</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. In determining under clause (2)(a) whether there is a genuine issue requiring a trial, the court shall consider the evidence submitted by the parties and, if the determination is being made by a judge, the judge may exercise any of the following powers for the purpose, unless it is in the interest of justice for such powers to be exercised at a trial:
<P1>1. Weighing the evidence.</P1>
<P1>2. Evaluating the credibility of a deponent.</P1>
<P1>3. Drawing any reasonable inference from the evidence.</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference: Rules of Civil Procedure, R.R.O. 1990, Reg. 194, as amended R. 20.04(2.1)</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>26. A two stage approach for determining if a genuine issue requiring a trial exists was set forth in <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Maulding</SOC></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>A judge on a summary judgment motion should:
<P1>i) Determine if there's a genuine issue requiring trial based only on the evidence before her, without using the new fact-finding powers. There will be no genuine issue requiring a trial if the summary judgment process provides her with the evidence required to fairly and justly adjudicate the dispute and it's a timely, affordable and proportionate procedure, under Rule 20.04(2)(a)</P1>
<P1>ii) If there is a genuine issue requiring a trial, the judge should then determine if the need for a trial can be avoided by using the new powers under Rules 20.04(2.1) and (2.2)</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Maul ding</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE></CASEREF>, <BOLD><EM>[Hryniak]</EM> at para.66.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>Genuine Issues Requiring a Trial Exist Regarding the Nature, Scope and Quality of the Legal Advice Given to Ms Virgo</TI>
<P>27. Where a creditor relies upon a spousal guarantee and has knowledge or out to have knowledge of irregularities and/or uncertainties in respect of the independent legal advice rendered, the creditor has a duty to take further steps to ensure that the advice given was truly independent and free from duress and that the guarantor full understood the scope of enforcement that could be brought against her.
<P1><BOLD>Reference:</BOLD>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Carevest Capital Inc. v. Starserra Homes (Riverside) Limited</SOC><CITE>2009 CanLII 25976</CITE><COURTJUR>ON SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at paragraphs 24&ndash;27</BOLD></P2>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Bank of Montreal v. Duguid</SOC><CITE>2000 CanLII 5710</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P2></P1></P>
<P>28. Given the divergent accounts of the deponents in this motion and the divergent positions of parties to the action with respect to the effect of the Guarantee, genuine issues of fact exist which will require a judge to make findings of fact and credibility based on hearing <EM>viva voce</EM> evidence.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>Genuine Issues Requiring a Trial Exist Regarding Whitely's Ability to Render Legal Advice</TI>
<P>29. Pursuant to the <EM>Law Society Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c L.8
<QUOTE><P>&ldquo;licensee&rdquo; means,</P>
<P>(a) a person licensed to practise law in Ontario as a barrister and solicitor, or</P>
<P>(b) a person licensed to provide legal services in Ontario; and</P>
<P>&ldquo;a person who is authorized to practise law in Ontario&rdquo; means,</P>
<P>(a) a person who is licensed to practise law in Ontario as a barrister and solicitor and whose licence is not suspended, or</P>
<P>(b) a person who is not a licensee but is permitted by the by-laws to practise law as a barrister and solicitor in Ontario</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference: <EM>Law Society Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c L.8, 1(1)</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>30. Pursuant to sections 5 and 6, in part of the <EM>Law Society Act</EM>,
<QUOTE><SEC><N>(5)</N><SECP>A person provides legal services if the person engages in conduct that involves the application of legal principles and legal judgment with regard to the circumstances or objectives of a person. 2006, c. 21, Sched. C, s. 2 (10).</SECP></SEC>
<SEC><N>(6)</N><SECP>Without limiting the generality of subsection (5), a person provides legal services if the person does any of the following:
<SSEC><N>1.</N><SSECP>Gives a person advice with respect to the legal interests, rights or responsibilities of the person or of another person.</SSECP></SSEC></SECP></SEC></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Reference: <EM>Law Society Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c L.8, s 5 and 6</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
